 the ability distribution were "insignificantly different from zero - and possibly negative for later [school] conversions.</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">  </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">meaning that the gap for disadvantaged children is not nar</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rowed by academisation </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence from The Academies Commission concluded that: "the evidence…does not suggest that improvement across all academies has been strong enough to transform the life chances of children from the poorest families" showed that "a</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cademy status alone is not a panacea for improvement" </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="color:#262626; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">considering that children at academies are four times more likely to receive a permanent exclusion compared to all schools, and </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="color:#1f2439; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hildren with an </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SEN continue to be over eight times more likely to be </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permanently excluded from school than the rest of the school population</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it is logical that a higher proportion of disabled children are more likely to be excluded if they attend academies.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ways in which academies can narrow the gap for disadvantaged c</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hildren include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Use of Technology In Academies</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="color:#3b454c; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ne in ten children between the ages of one and 15 has a mental health disorder</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="color:#3b454c; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">61,570 children in state-funded schools who are recorded as having some kind of autistic spectrum disorder (ASD)</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  These</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> two figures alone are terrifying and it is vital that support is given to these young people in education or they will have a higher chance of ending up on the NEETs register.  </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Indeed, only 15% of adults with autism in the UK are in full-time paid </span><a href="http://www.autism.org.uk/en-GB/Our-services/Employment-support.aspx"><span style="color:#4c2b52; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="color:#4c2b52; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="color:#4c2b52; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ployment</span></a><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">attending school is much harder for a vulnerable young person due to wellbeing, health or bullying issues, the use of o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nline and blended learning can be adapted to the mainstream environment to allow these young people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to focus on learning without being bogged down by external influences, which they may struggle to deal with.  In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it can help to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">promote best pract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ice as any academy involved in the project can pass this information on electronically to others increasing understanding and standards overall.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nisai Virtual Academy (NVA) – created by the Nisai Group delivers the National Curriculum together with so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me Vocational Qualifications and is completely interactive, allowing students to engage in live lessons with teachers and other students as well as move around the online campus, whilst using the same frameworks as a student would receive in a traditional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">school.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">young people using </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Nisai Virtual Academy have an entire virtual support team around them including their subject tutors and a specially assigned tutor to deal with their personal wellbeing.  This has proved to be a very </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successful route for vulnerable young people, and can help them get the support they need to deal better with their mainstream lessons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reduction of Exclusions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#4d4d4f; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#4d4d4f; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here needs to be a rethink regarding the recommendation made by PricewaterhouseCoopers regarding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“a system for monitoring exclusions in Academies … and provide support to Academies, similar to that provided through Local Authority Behaviour Support Teams… </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to reduce the disproportionate number of exclusions in some Academies”.  This will help to make sure that disadvantaged students are not being unfairly excluded and that students are given the help and education they need if they are excluded for example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through the use of online and blended learning tools.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#4d4d4f; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> http://www.teachers.org.uk/node/19715</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> http://www.thersa.org/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/1008038/Unleashing-greatness.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Statistical First Release: Permanent and Fixed Period Exclusions From Schools and Exclusion Appeals in England, 2009/10, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">Department for Education, 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="color:#3b454c; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">The Office for National Statistics Mental health in chil